Description: Stamp-seal in limestone (?); in the shape of a squat, double-plumed cartouche, with a bundled handle; underside bears a carved hieroglyphic inscription, combining a hill sign, a scarab and a sun-disc; some incised details in feathers and signs; edges chipped.
Curator's comments: The inscription is seen as an imitation of a royal prenomen (Hall 1913, 284, no. 2741). Stamps with bundled handle such as this are common (see for example Hornung, Staehelin 1976, no. 588). Khakheperra is the prenomen of the 12th dynasty pharaoh Senusret II (1897–1878 BC), which would be a far too early date for this seal. Hall, H.R. 1913, Catalogue of Egyptian Scarabs, etc., in the British Museum, Vol. I Royal Scarabs, London,. Hornung, E. and Staehelin, E. 1976, Skarabäen und andere Siegelamulette aus Basler Sammlungen, Ägyptische Denkmäler in der Schweiz I.
Bibliographic references: Villing et al 2013-2015 / Naukratis: Greeks in Egypt (PA.07) (phase 3)
